Certainly! Here's an example MATLAB code that incorporates multiple factors, including material characteristics, to estimate the range of an RFID tag:

```matlab
% Constants
freq = 900e6; % RFID system frequency in Hz
power = 1; % Transmitted power in watts
distance = linspace(1, 10, 100); % Distance between tag and reader in meters

% Material properties
conductivity = 5e6; % Material conductivity in S/m (example value)
relative_permittivity = 4; % Relative permittivity (example value)

% Calculation of reflection loss
reflection_coefficient = ((377 * sqrt(relative_permittivity) - conductivity) / ...
    (377 * sqrt(relative_permittivity) + conductivity));
reflection_loss = 20 * log10(abs(reflection_coefficient));

% Calculation of skin depth
skin_depth = sqrt(2 / (pi * freq * 4e-7 * conductivity));

% Calculation of range with material effects
range_with_material = (power / (10^((reflection_loss + 2 * distance / skin_depth) / 10)));

% Plotting the results
figure;
plot(distance, range_with_material);
xlabel('Distance (m)');
ylabel('Range');
title('RFID Tag Range with Material Effects');
```

In this code, you can modify the values for `conductivity` and `relative_permittivity` to match the properties of the material in consideration. The code calculates the reflection loss using the reflection coefficient equation and then determines the range based on the reflection loss and skin depth at different distances. Finally, it plots the range as a function of distance.

Please note that this is a simplified example, and actual range calculations in real-world scenarios may require more complex models and further considerations of other factors.
